# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

llama.cpp has two chat-template systems:
- **Legacy** (`src/llama-chat.cpp` + `src/llama-chat.h`): enum-keyed C++ implementations, auto-detection via heuristic string matching in `llm_chat_detect_template()`.
- **Modern Jinja** (`common/chat.cpp`): renders Jinja2 templates; specialized handlers in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` intercept specific template shapes before the generic autoparser runs.

The existing Ministral 3 specialized handler fires when the Jinja source contains `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`. The Mistral Instruct v0.3 format uses `[INST]/[/INST]` but never `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, so it falls through unhandled. The task is to add a new specialized handler for that format in the **modern Jinja path only**, touching no existing handlers and no header files.

---

## Files to Modify

| File | Action |
|------|--------|
| `common/chat.cpp` | Add one new static function + one new `if`-block in the dispatcher |

**Do NOT touch:** `src/llama-chat.h`, `src/llama-chat.cpp`, or any existing handler function.

---

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1 — Add the new handler function in `common/chat.cpp`

**Where:** Insert immediately after the closing `}` of `common_chat_params_init_ministral_3` (currently ends at **line 940**), before `common_chat_params_init_gpt_oss` starts at line 942.

**New function** (`common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3`):

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
    const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
    const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 format:
    //   [INST] {optional system\n\n}{user} [/INST] {assistant}</s> [INST] {user} [/INST] …
    // System messages are prepended inside the first [INST] block.
    common_chat_params data;
    std::string prompt;
    bool is_inside_turn = false;

    for (const auto & msg : inputs.messages) {
        const auto role = msg.value("role", "");
        std::string content;
        if (msg.contains("content") && msg.at("content").is_string()) {
            content = msg.at("content").get<std::string>();
        }

        if (role == "system") {
            if (!is_inside_turn) {
                prompt += "[INST] ";
                is_inside_turn = true;
            }
            prompt += content + "\n\n";
        } else if (role == "user") {
            if (!is_inside_turn) {
                prompt += "[INST] ";
                is_inside_turn = true;
            }
            prompt += content + " [/INST]";
        } else if (role == "assistant") {
            prompt += " " + content + "</s>";
            is_inside_turn = false;
        }
    }

    data.prompt = std::move(prompt);
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;
    return data;
}
```

**Key design choices:**
- `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY` — no grammar, no PEG parser, no preserved tokens needed for this simple format.
- System role opens an `[INST]` block if one isn't already open, matching the behaviour of the legacy `MISTRAL_V3` handler in `llama-chat.cpp` (lines 267-291).
- Content is extracted as a plain string; multimodal/array content is left as `""` (acceptable for this basic text format).
- No explicit `add_generation_prompt` suffix is required: for inference the prompt naturally ends with ` [/INST]` after the last user message, which is the correct generation boundary.

---

### Step 2 — Register with auto-detection in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`

**Where:** In `common/chat.cpp`, inside `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`, immediately after the closing `}` of the Ministral 3 block (**after line 1644**).

**New detection block:**

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v3 - uses [INST]/[/INST] without [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
// Distinguishes from the Ministral/Magistral Large 3 handler above which requires [SYSTEM_PROMPT].
if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
}
```

**Detection logic:**
- `[INST]` present → identifies the template as a Mistral-family `[INST]/[/INST]` format.
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absent → distinguishes from Ministral 3 (and Mistral V7/V7-Tekken) which use a separate `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]...[/SYSTEM_PROMPT]` block.
- Placed **after** the Ministral 3 check so the more-specific handler wins when both markers are present.

---

## Produced output format (example)

Given messages: `system="Be helpful"`, `user="Hello"`, `assistant="Hi"`, `user="Bye"`:

```
[INST] Be helpful\n\nHello [/INST] Hi</s>[INST] Bye [/INST]
```

---

## Verification

1. **Unit test** — In `tests/test-chat-template.cpp`, add a test case that exercises the new handler with a synthetic Jinja source string containing `[INST]` but not `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, and assert the formatted prompt matches the expected `[INST] … [/INST] … </s>` pattern.

2. **Manual smoke test** — Run `llama-cli` with a Mistral Instruct v0.3 GGUF (e.g., `mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3`) and confirm:
   - System message appears inside the first `[INST]` block.
   - User turns are wrapped with `[INST] … [/INST]`.
   - Assistant turns end with `</s>`.

3. **Regression** — Run the existing test suite (`make test-chat-template`) to confirm no existing template handler behaviour changed.

